title: Impeachment inquiry into Bill Clinton
added: The ''Starr Report'' was released on September 11, 1998.
=== Earlyactionsbythe House Committee on the Judiciary ===

Despite the objections of Democrats, the [[House Committee on the Judiciary]] agreed to release the videotape of Clinton's grand jury testimony and more the 3,000 pages of the ''Starr Report'''s supporting material, including a sexually explicit testimony by Lewinsky. This content was released on September 21.<ref name="CUNY">{{cite web |title=Clinton impeachment timeline |url=http://academic.brooklyn.cuny.edu/history/johnson/clintontimeline.htm |website=academic.brooklyn.cuny.edu |publisher=City University of New York |access-date=1 March 2021}}</ref>
The committee announced on September 24 that, in an open session on either October 5 or 6, it would consider a resolution that would initiate an impeachment inquiry against Clinton.<ref name="CUNY"/>

On October 2, the committee released 4,610 more pages of supporting material from the Starr investigation, a cache which included transcripts of grand jury testimony and transcripts of the recordings [[Linda Tripp]] made of phone calls she had with Lewinsky.<ref name="CUNY"/>
On October 5, in a 21â€“16 vote, the House Committee on the judiciary recommended a formal impeachment inquiry.<ref name="CUNY"/>

title: Impeachment inquiry into Bill Clinton
added: On November 19, Ken Starr presented his case against Clinton to the House Committee on the Judiciary. Starr declared that Clinton had repeatedly chosen "deception".<ref name="CUNY"/> In this session, the Democrats on the committee questioned Starr on his methods of investigation.<ref name="CUNY"/>

On November 28, Clinton delivered written answers to 81 questions that the House Committee on the Judiciary had given him.<ref>{{cite web |title=TESTING OF A PRESIDENT; Clinton's Responses to Questions From the House Judiciary Committee (Published 1998) |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/11/28/us/testing-president-clinton-s-responses-questions-house-judiciary-committee.html |website=The New York Times |access-date=1 March 2021 |date=28 November 1998}}</ref><ref name="CNN28nov">{{cite web |title=Republicans disappointed by Clinton's answers to impeachment questions - November 28, 1998 |url=https://www.cnn.com/ALLPOLITICS/stories/1998/11/28/impeach.republicans/ |website=www.cnn.com |publisher=CNN | agency=AllPolitics |access-date=1 March 2021 |date=28 November 1998}}</ref> Republicans voiced disappointment and outrage at Clinton's questions, which they criticized as being evasive, incomplete, weak in defense, and legalistic.<ref name="CUNY"/><ref name="CNN28nov"/>

title: Impeachment inquiry into Bill Clinton
added: Per [[Pew Research Center]] [[polling]], the impeachment process against Clinton was generally unpopular.<ref>{{cite web |title=Clinton's impeachment barely dented his public support, and it turned off many Americans |url=https://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2019/10/03/clintons-impeachment-barely-dented-his-public-support-and-it-turned-off-many-americans/ |website=Pew Research Center |access-date=28 February 2021}}</ref>
